            "layout": "centered",
            "eyebrow": "THE PROBLEM",
            "heading": "What we saw in 2020",
            "body": "<p>Walk into any Indian supermarket and pick up a 'probiotic' yogurt. Read the label. The strains aren't named, the count isn't disclosed, and the pasteurisation step has killed every live bacterium on the way to the shelf.</p><p>Meanwhile, the dahi your grandmother set on the counter overnight, or the kanji your mother fermented in winter, was the real thing — billions of live <em>Lactobacillus</em> doing what they've done in Indian kitchens for centuries.</p><p>Somewhere in the last 30 years, we replaced that with shelf-stable factory yogurt and called it progress.</p>"
          }
